04778nam a22007215i 9781501731860DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20181996nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017318607 a10.7591/97815017318602doi  a(DE-B1597)515421  a(OCoLC)1129161940  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0230002bisacsh04a330.95691/0422231 aLawson, Fred H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhy Syria Goes to War :bThirty Years of Confrontation /cFred H. Lawson. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b1 map, 19 graphs, 2 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Political Economy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tTables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Linking Domestic Conflict to Foreign Policy -- t1. Provoking Confrontation with Israel, 1967 -- t2. Limiting Intervention in Jordan, 1970 -- t3. Expanding Intervention in Lebanon, 1976 -- t4. Defusing Confrontation with Iraq, 1982 -- t5. Abjuring Confrontation with Turkey, 1994 -- t6. Domestic Conflict and Crisis Escalation in a Liberal- Democratic Syria -- tConclusion: Implications for Further Research -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRejecting conventional explanations for Syrian foreign policy, which emphasize the personalities and attitudes of leaders, cultural factors peculiar to Arab societies, or the machinations of the great powers, Fred H. Lawson describes key shifts in Damascus's response to regional adversaries in terms of changes in the intensity of political struggles at home. Periodic eruptions of domestic conflict have inspired Syria's ruling coalition to adopt a wide range of programs designed to buy off domestic rivals and perpetuate the predominance of individual coalition members. These programs have undermined the unity of the Ba'thi regime, increasing the chances that opponents will overturn the established order. Challenges to the Ba'thi regime become most threatening whenever crises of accumulation shake the domestic political economy, Lawson contends. Opposition forces gain strength when the state cannot sustain new investment or when competition increases between public and private enterprises. Political and economic trends inside Syria have determined why Damascus has since 1963 alternately escalated tensions with regional rivals and adopted more accommodating postures. Lawson traces this dynamic through five major episodes: the 1967 war with Israel; limited intervention in Jordan in 1970; the widening conflict in Lebanon in 1976; the defusing of conflict with Iraq in 1982; and the rapprochement with Turkey over Kurdish separatism in 1994. These patterns, Lawson suggests, may be characteristic of nations changing from one domestic economic system to a radically different one, as Syria has in the transition from state socialism to a privatized political economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArab-Israeli conflictxEconomic aspectszSyria. 0aWarxEconomic aspectszSyria. 4aMiddle East Studies. 4aMilitary History. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173186040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501731860423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501731860.jpg  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-